The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, Aug. 24: Samsung India, a subsidiary of Samsung Electronics, plans to set up a second manufacturing facility in India as it eyes sales in excess of Rs 9,000 crore by 2008. The local as well as the parent company will fund the plant, said Ravinder Zutshi, deputy managing director of Samsung India. Zutshi refused to elaborate on the location of the new plant or the products that it will manufacture.

 Mumbai, Aug. 24: Tata-run Videsh Sanchar Nigam Ltd today slashed its international bandwidth prices by 25 to 40 per cent and announced plans to establish two new submarine cable systems at an investment of $600 million. Of the two cable systems, one will be between India and Europe, while the other will cover the Asian region. They will interconnect with VSNLs existing global network. The India-Europe cable will also provide connectivity to the Gulf region and the African continent.

 Kuala Lumpur, Aug. 24: Asean today demanded that India make further tariff concessions in its list of goods and services offered under a beleaguered free trade agreement (FTA) as the two sides agreed to resume FTA talks suspended by the 10-member group because of alleged lack of progress.

 Stockholm, Aug. 24: Swedish telecom group Ericsson has won an order worth about $1 billion from Bharti Airtel to expand and upgrade its mobile network.




